Saket Siddharth and Ravishankar Rai V*  A rare actinobacteria strain designated SCA21, producing bioactive metabolites was isolated  from marine sediment of Havelock Island, Andaman and Nicobar Islands, India. Analysis of  16S  rRNA  sequences  suggested  that  the  strain  SCA21  belonged  to  the  genus  Nocardiopsis.  Chemical  investigation  of  the  fermentation  broth  led  to  the  isolation  of  two  pure  bioactive  compounds (1-2). Compound 1: 4-bromophenol, a bromophenol derivative; Compound 2: Bis  (2-ethylhexyl)  phthalate,  a  phthalate  ester.  The  structure  of  compound  1  and  2  were  elucidated  by  the  detailed  analysis  of  FT-IR,  HR-ESI-MS,  1D  and  2D  NMR,  along  with  literature  data  analysis.  The  isolated  metabolites  were  evaluated  for  enzyme  inhibition  activity against α-glucosidase and α-amylase, free radical scavenging activity against DPPH  and  ABTS  radicals,  metal  chelating  and  antibacterial  activity  against  clinical  pathogens.  1  and  2  exhibited  remarkable  enzyme  inhibitory  activities  against  α-glucosidase.  However,  Compound 2 was found less active against α-amylase. They showed significant free radical  scavenging  activity  against  DPPH  and  ABTS  radicals.  In  addition,  except  the  strain  Salmonella typhi ATCC 25241 and Listeria cytogens ATCC 13932,  1 and 2 showed broad  spectrum  inhibitory  activity  against  MRSA  ATCC  NR-46171,  MRSA  ATCC-46071,  Klebsiella  pneumonia  ATCC  13883,  Bacillus  subtilis  ATCC  6633,  Staphylococcus  aureus

ATCC  12600.  In  conclusion,  to  best  of  our  knowledge  these  findings  are  the  first  report  of  isolation  of  4-bromophenol  and  Bis  (2-ethylhexyl)  phthalate  from  genus  Nocardiopsis,  thus  suggesting  that  rare  actinomycetes  are  promising  source  of  therapeutically  important  Keywords:  Marine  organisms;  Nocardiopsis;  bioactive  compounds;  antibacterial;  antioxidants; enzyme inhibitors  Actinobacteria  are  prolific  producers  of  secondary  metabolites  with  varying  chemical  diversity  possessing  strong  biological  activities  [1].  Of  antimalarial,  antibacterial,  immunosuppressant,  anti-tumor,  enzyme  inhibitors,  antioxidant,  cytotoxic  drugs  are  of  pharmaceutical  importance  [2].  Actinobacterial  derived  bioactive  metabolites account for approximately 70% of the naturally occurring compound currently in  clinical  use  [3].  Majority  of  the  secondary  metabolites  are  generated  through  enzyme  catalysed multi-step biosynthetic pathways [4].  actinobacteria with unique chemical structure. These habitats facilitate wide array of organic  compounds which are metabolized by the microorganisms for their growth, development and  metabolite  production  [5].  The  microbial  biodiversity  of  marine  ecosystem  is  a  potential  resource  for  exploring  novel  bioactive  metabolites.  Although  many  studies  suggested  the  importance  of  the  metabolites  from  the  genus  Streptomyces  isolated  from  marine  habitats,  only  few  reported  the  rare  actinobacteria  derived  metabolites.  Therefore,  bioprospecting  of  promising  rare  actinobacterial  strains  producing  potential  metabolites  holds  a  great  promise  and have been a major part of research [6]. Screening and isolation of promising strains from  the marine samples of different geographical locations have led to the identification of genus

Nocardiopsis.  The  member  of  genus  Nocardiopsis  are  gram-positive,  aerobic,  catalase  positive,  non-acid  fast  and  their  cell  walls  contain  meso  2,6-diaminopimelic  acid  [7].  They  are  predominantly  present  and  are  able  to  prevail  under  extreme  environments  including  salterns,  desert,  marine,  mine  tailings,  alkaline  and  hypersaline  regions  because  of  their  genetic  make-up,  secretion  of  extremozymes,  solutes  and  surfactants  and  an  array  of  bioactive  compounds  that  may  aid  in  survival  under  adverse  conditions  [8].  The  genus  Nocardiopsis is one of the rare actinobacteria which has potential to produce wide variety of  chemical classes of compounds with varying biological activities [9]. The present study was  undertaken to evaluate the bioactive potential of secondary metabolites produced by the rare  actinobacteria from marine sediment of Havelock Island, Andaman and Nicobar Islands. The  metabolites produced by Nocardiopsis sp. SCA21 were purified, characterized and assessed  for  their  inhibitory  effects  against  α-glucosidase  and  α-amylase  enzymes,  antioxidant  and  antibacterial activities.   2. Materials and Methods  2.1. Sampling, pre-treatment and Isolation of Actinobacteria  Unexplored  marine  environments  usually  have  more  chance  of  harbouring  them  antiviral,  antifungal,

The marine sediment samples were  collected  from different locations of  Havelock  Island, a  part of Indian union territory of Andaman and Nicobar Islands (Latitude 11.96o N, Longitude  93.00o  E).  Samples  were  brought  to  the  laboratory  aseptically  in  dry  sterile  insulated  container and stored at 4oC until further laboratory analysis. The collected samples were air  dried for 7 days at room temperature and kept at hot air oven at 50oC for 96 hrs. Pre-treated  samples were ground aseptically with mortar and pestle and serially diluted up to 10-6 in ten- fold  dilution.  The  aliquots  of  each  dilution  (100  µL)  was  spread  onto  starch  casein  agar  (SCA, Himedia) prepared in 50% sterile sea water and supplemented with cycloheximide (50  µg/mL)  and nalidixic acid (25 µg/mL). The plates were incubated at 28oC for 3 weeks and  observed  for  growth.  Pure  colonies  were  maintained  on  International  Streptomyces  Project  (ISP-2, Himedia) agar slants and stored at 4oC as working stock.   2.2. Molecular characterization of 16S rRNA gene and phylogenetic analysis  The  PCR  amplification  of  16S  rRNA  gene  of  the  strain  SCA21  was  carried  out  by  using  universal  primers:  27F  (5’-AGA  GTT  TGA  TCC  TGG  CTC  AG-3’)  and  1492R  (5’-  ACG  GCT  ACC  TTG  TTA  CGA  CTT-3’).  The  amplified  PCR  product  were  sequenced  and  compared  with  relative  16S  rRNA  gene  sequences  obtained  from  BLAST  search.  The  resultant sequences were submitted to NCBI database. The genetic relationship between the  strains was determined by neighbour-joining method. The phylogenetic tree was constructed

with  bootstrapped  database  containing  1000  replicates  in  MEGA  7.0  software  (Mega,  2.3. Cultivation, Extraction and purification of bioactive metabolites   Inoculant of strain SCA21 was prepared in ISP-2 broth (seed medium) and incubated at 28oC  for  2  weeks  while  shaking  at  150  rev  min-1.  After  incubation,  5  mL  of  seed  medium  was  transferred  aseptically  to  95  mL  of  production  medium  (ISP-2)    and  was  incubated  at  28oC  for  2  weeks.  45L  of  culture  medium  was  prepared  by  same  method.  After  incubation,  the  medium  was  centrifuged  at  10,000  rpm  for  15  min  and  the  crude  metabolites  were  isolated  from  cultured  supernatant.  The  culture  filtrate  was  therefore  extracted  thrice  with  equal  volume of ethyl acetate. The mixture was shaken vigorously and kept stationary overnight for  separation  of  organic  phase  from  aqueous  phase.  The  organic  phase  was  separated  and  concentrated under rotary vacuum concentrator. The crude extract thus obtained was dried in  a desiccator for few days. The dried extract was loaded onto glass column measuring 4.5 cm  diameter x 50 cm height packed with silica gel (60-120 and 100-200 mesh silica gel; Sigma  chemicals Co., USA). Slurry of crude extract and silica gel was eluted with step wise gradient  solvent system in the ratio 10:90. The eluent varied from non-polar solvents to polar solvents  (Hexane-chloroform-ethyl  acetate-acetone-methanol).  The  fractions  (50ml)  were  collected  and validated by thin layer chromatography. The fractions with same Rf value were combined  and  evaluated  for  bioactivities.  The  purity  of  each  collected  fraction  was  determined  by

reverse  phase  HPLC  (Shimadzu,  LC-20,  Japan).  The  fractions  were  injected  onto  C-18  column (5 µm; 250x4.60 mm) with gradient run of HPLC grade water and acetonitrile (10- 100%) for 30 min at a flow rate of 0.5 mL/min with detection at 254 nm.   2.4. Identification and characterization of bioactive metabolites  The  structural  elucidation  of  the  compounds  was  determined  by  spectroscopic  analysis  including  NMR  and  HR-ESI-MS.  1H  and  13C  NMR  were  carried  out  on  AM-500  FT-NMR  spectrometer  (Bruker,  Rheinstetten,  Germany)  using  tetramethylsilane  (TMS)  as  internal  reference.  The  mass  spectrum  of  the  purified  active  compounds  was  recorded  by  ion  trap  method  and  m/z  was  reported  in  atomic  mass  units  by  HR-ESI-MS  (XEVO  G2-XS  QTOF,  WATERS,  UK).  The  presence  of  functional  groups  was  determined  by  FT-IR  spectrophotometer in the range of 400-4000 cm-1 (Perkin Elmer, USA).  2.5.1. Antibacterial assay  The antibacterial  activity of purified compounds  (1 and 2) was performed by  disc-diffusion  method  on  Mueller-Hinton  agar  medium  and  minimum  inhibitory  concentration  (MIC)  of  purified  compounds  was  determined  by  micro  dilution  method  as  previously  reported  by  Siddharth and Vittal  [10]. The test organisms (Klebsiella pneumoniae ATCC 13883, Listeria  cytogens ATCC 13932, Staphylococcus aureus ATCC 12600, Bacillus subtilis ATCC 6633,

Salmonella  typhi  ATCC  25241,  MRSA  ATCC  NR-46171,  MRSA  ATCC  NR-46071)  were  procured  from  American  Type  Culture  Collection  (ATCC,  Manassas,  VA,  USA).  Gentamycin  discs  (Himedia)  were  used  as  positive  control.    Discs  impregnated  with  0.1%  DMSO were used as solvent control.  Briefly, 100 µL of overnight grown suspension of each  bacterial  pathogen  was  evenly  spread  onto  Mueller  Hinton  agar  plates.  Compound  1  and  2  were  dissolved  in  DMSO  to  give  final  concentration  of  10  mg/mL  and  30  µL  of  each  compound was added to paper disc. The discs were air-dried  and placed  onto plates seeded  with  pathogens  and  incubated  at  37oC  for  12  hr.  The  diameter  of  zone  of  inhibition  was  measured. 2.5.2. 2,2-diphenyl -1-picrylhydrazyl Radical Scavenging assay (DPPH)  Radical scavenging activity is based upon the reduction of highly stable DPPH free radicals  to  DPPH-H  by  the  hydrogen  donating  antioxidants.  Freshly  prepared  DPPH  solution  in  methanol (60mM, Sigma) was mixed vigorously with two-fold diluted serial concentration of  purified  compounds  (1  and  2)  and  added  to  96-well  plates.  The  reaction  mixture  was  incubated for 20 min in the dark. The absorbance of each well was measured at 520 nm. The  decrease  in  the  absorbance  value  of  reaction  mixture  indicates  an  increase  in  the  radical  scavenging  activity. Where, Ao = Absorbance of control, A1 = Absorbance of purified compounds. Trolox (Sigma)  was used as a reference compound whereas methanol was used as blank [11].  2.5.3. Metal chelating activity  The  metal  chelating  activity  is  based  upon  the  ability  of  the  compounds  to  compete  with  ferrozine for Fe2+. The assay was performed according to the method previously described by  Adjimani  and  Asare  [12]  with  slight  modifications.  The  reduction  in  colour  intensity  as  a  result  of  disruption  of  Fe2+  and  ferrozine  complexes  was  measured  spectrophotometrically.  The reaction mixture containing two-fold diluted serial concentration of purified compounds  (1 and 2) and 0.1 mL FeCl2 (2mM) was added to ferrozine (5mM, Sigma) and incubated at  room  temperature  for  15  min.  The  absorbance  was  measured  at  562  nm.  The  chelating  activity was calculated as:  Where, Ao = Absorbance of control, A1 = Absorbance of purified compounds. EDTA was  used as a positive control.   2.5.4.  2,20-Azino-bis(3-ethylbenzothiazoline-6-sulfonic  acid)  radical  scavenging  assay  ABTS  radical  scavenging  activity  is  based  upon  the  reduction  of  ABTS*+  radicals  by  the  antioxidants  of  low  redox  potential  than  ABTS.  The  assay  was  performed  according  to  the  method  developed  by  Ser  et  al.  [13]  with  slight  modifications.  Initially,  ABTS  cation  complex  was  prepared  by  mixing  stock  ABTS  solution  (7mM)  with  potassium  persulfate  (2.45 mM) and incubated in the dark at room temperature for 12-16 hrs. The absorbance of

the  solution  was  adjusted  to  0.7  ±  0.01  units  with  buffered  saline  (pH  7.2)  at  734  nm. The reaction mixture was incubated for 30  min  in  the  dark  and  absorbance  of  each  well  was  measured  at  415  nm. Trolox (Sigma)  was used as a positive reference.    2.5.5 α-glucosidase inhibition assay  The α-glucosidase inhibitory activity of the compounds was determined by calorimetric assay  as  previously  assessed  by  Dong  et  al.  [14]  with  slight  modifications.  In  brief,  50  µL  of  α- glucosidase  (0.2  U/mL,  Sigma)  prepared  in  0.1  M  phosphate  buffer  (pH  7.0)  and  different  concentrations  of  purified  compounds  (1  and  2)  ranging  from  (3.90-500  µg/mL)  were  pre- incubated in 96-well plates at 37oC for 20 min. The reaction was initiated with addition of 50  µL of p-nitrophenyl-α-D-glucopyranoside (5mM pNPG, Sigma) solution in 0.1 M phosphate  buffer  (pH  7.0).  The  reaction  mixture  was  incubated  at  37oC  for  another  20  min.  After

incubation, the reaction was stopped by adding 100 µL of 0.1 M Na2CO3 and absorbance was  measured at 405 nm by UV spectrophotometer (Shimadzu, Kyoto, Japan). Acarbose was used  as  a  positive  control,  whereas  phosphate  buffer  replaced  purified  compounds  in  control.  Buffer  solution  was  used  in  blank  mixture  and  absorbance  was  recorded.    Each  experiment  was  performed  in  triplicate.  The  α-glucosidase  inhibitory  activity  was  expressed  as  percentage inhibition by using the following equation:            percentage inhibition (%) = absorbance of control – absorbance of sample X 100                                                                             absorbance of control  2.5.6. α-amylase inhibition assay  The  α-amylase  inhibitory  activity  of  the  purified  compounds  (1  and  2)  was  determined  by  calorimetric  method  reported  previously  by  Siddharth  and  Vittal  [15]  with  slight  modifications. 0.5 mg/mL of α-amylase enzyme (Sigma) in 50mM phosphate buffer (pH 7.0)  was incubated with different concentrations of purified compounds at 37oC for 10 min. 50 µL  of 1% starch solution was added to pre-incubated mixture and further incubated at 37oC for  another  10  min.  The  reaction  was  ceased  by  adding  100  µL  of  DNS  reagent  (Sigma),  incubated at 95oC for 10 min and cooled to room temperature. Absorbance was recorded at  540  nm. 3.1. Isolation and characterization of marine actinobacteria  Andaman and Nicobar Islands known for their rich biodiversity are yet to be explored to their  potential. The marine sediment samples were collected from the sites comprised of chain of  islands to the east of Great Andaman. The pre-treated samples were serially diluted up to 10-6  in ten-fold dilution. Eleven morphologically distinct colonies were observed in dilution 10-4.  Each colony was streaked on to starch casein agar medium. The actinobacterial isolate grown  on  starch  casein  agar  medium  (petri  dish  no.  9)  appeared  as  powdery  colonies  with  light  cream  aerial  mycelium,  light  brown  substrate  mycelium  with  no  diffusible  pigments  was  chosen  for  this  study  (Fig.  1a).  The  aerial  mycelium  bearing  long  chain  of  fragmenting  branched  smooth  spores  was  observed  under  scanning  electron  microscope  (Fig.  1b).  It  possessed  gram-positive,  aerobic,  non-acid  fast  and  non-motile  characteristics.  Multiple  sequence alignment and analysis of the 16S rRNA gene segment compared with the obtained  sequences  from  NCBI  gene  database  confirmed  that  the  strain  SCA21  belonged  to  genus  Nocardiopsis  as  it  exhibited  sequence  similarity  of  96.81%  with  that  of  Nocardiopsis  dassonvillei  strain  XY236  (accession  no:  MH432693.1),  Nocardiopsis  dassonvillei  subsp.  albirubida strain ZM3-1 (accession no: MH027603.1), Nocardiopsis synnemataformans strain  AlS2  (accession  no:  MF321793.1).  The  obtained  sequences  were  deposited  in  NCBI  GenBank  under  accession  number  MH105056.  The  taxonomic  position  of  the  strain  with

respect to its closest relatives was shown by phylogenetic tree constructed using MEGA 7.0  Fig. 1: a) Morphological characteristics of Nocardiopsis sp. SCA21 grown on starch casein  agar b) Scanning electron micrograph showing long chains of fragmenting branched smooth  ornamentation of spores in Nocardiopsis sp. SCA21 isolated from Havelock Island, Andaman  and Nicobar Islands, India  Fig.  2:  Phylogenetic  tree  derived  from  16S  rRNA  gene  sequences  showing  the  relationship  between Nocardiopsis sp. SCA21 and other related species belonging to genus Nocardiopsis  using the neighbour-joining method.   3.2. Extraction and purification of bioactive metabolites  The strain SCA21 cultured on 45 litre of ISP-2 medium was extracted three times with ethyl  acetate  (EtOAc)  to  yield  2.45  g  of  crude  extract.  The  dark  brown  semi  solid  (oily  texture)  crude  extract  exhibited  antagonistic  activity  against  bacterial  pathogens,  free  radicals  scavenging  activity,  metal  chelating  activity  and  significant  inhibition  potential  against  α- amylase and α-glucosidase enzymes. The EtOAc extract was subjected to fractionation using  silica gel column chromatography (hexane-chloroform-ethyl acetate-acetone-methanol 10:90,  v/v)  yielding  five  fractions  SF1-SF5.  Each  fraction  was  assayed  for  bioactivities.  Active  fractions  SF1  (94  mg)  and  SF4  (116  mg)  were  further  purified  by  silica  gel  column  eluted  with  ethyl  acetate  and  methanol  (100-200  mesh;  25:1-1:1)  yielding  two  (SF1.1,  SF1.2)  and  three (SF4.1, SF4.2 and SF4.3) sub-fractions respectively. Of them, active sub-fraction SF1.1

(Compound  1,  36mg)  and  SF4.2  (Compound  2,  28mg)  were  considered  for  further  characterization.  The  purity  of  the  active  compounds  was  determined  by  HPLC  eluted  with  gradient  run  of  HPLC  grade  water  and  acetonitrile  (10-100%).  A  sharp  peak  at  a  retention  time of 2.97 and 8.81 min was observed for compound 1 and 2 respectively (Fig. 3a and 3b).            Fig. 3: HPLC profile of a) compound 1 and b) compound 2 monitored at 254 nm   3.3. Identification of bioactive metabolites  The structural elucidation of active compounds was determined by HR-ESI-MS, 1D and 2D  NMR and FT-IR. The active compounds 1 and 2 showed molecular ion peak at m/z 172.94  (C6H5BrO) and m/z 391.28 (C24H38O4) [M+H]+ respectively (Fig. 4a and 4b). The structure  of the compounds was further confirmed by following detailed spectroscopic analysis:  Compound 1: 4-bromophenol, Colourless oil. IR vMAX/cm-1: 3352, 1589, 1433, 1488, 1335,  1116, 1069, 1240, 1172, 1218, 934, 825, 809, 694, 654, 637, 604 (Fig. 5a). 1H NMR (CDCl3,

400 MHz): δH 4.96 (S-OH), δH 6.69-6.72 (d, Ar-H, J= 9.2 Hz), δH 7.33-7.24 (d, Ar-H, J=34.4  Hz).  13C  NMR  (CDCl3,  150  MHz):  δC  112.96  (C4’),  δC  117.19  (C2’,C6’),  δC  132.48  (C3’,C5’),  δC  154.49  (C1’)  (Fig.  6).  On  the  basis  of  spectral  data,  the  structure  of  the  pure  compound 1 was identified as 4-bromophenol (Fig. 8a).  Compound 2: Bis(2-ethylhexyl) phthalate, Pale yellow oil. Antibacterial activity of bioactive metabolites  The antibacterial activity of compound 1 and 2 are shown in (Table 1a and 1b). The assay  used  paper  disc  diffusion  method  with  gentamycin  as  a  positive  control  and  DMSO  as  a  solvent control. Both compound 1 and 2 showed broad spectrum antagonistic activity against

gram-positive  and  gram-negative  pathogens  (Klebsiella  pneumoniae  ATCC  13883,  Listeria  cytogens ATCC 13932, Staphylococcus aureus ATCC 12600, Bacillus subtilis ATCC 6633,  Salmonella  typhi  ATCC  25241,  MRSA  ATCC  NR-46171,  MRSA  ATCC  NR-46071)  as  evidenced  by  bacteria-free  zone  on  Mueller-Hinton  agar  plates  (MHA)  (Fig.  9a  and  9b).  Compound  1  showed  significant  inhibitory  activity  against  Bacillus  subtilis  ATCC  6633  (26±0.12)  with  MIC  of  7.81  µg/mL.  The  MIC  value  of  compound  1  against  bacterial  pathogens was in the range of 7.81-125 µg/mL. Salmonella typhi ATCC 25241 were found to  be least susceptible to compound 1 as no growth inhibition was not observed.  Compound 2  showed strong inhibitory activity against Bacillus subtilis ATCC 6633 (22±0.30) and MRSA  ATCC  NR-46171  (20±0.41)  with  MIC  of  7.81µg/mL.  However,  it  did  not  exhibit  any  inhibitory  activity  against  Listeria  cytogens  ATCC  13932  and  Salmonella  typhi  ATCC  25241. They  are  mainly  categorised  into  polyketides [17], alkaloids [18], macrolides [19], diketopiperazines [20], napthoquinones [21]  and phenoxazine derivatives [22] showing range of biological activities including antifungal

[23]  antibacterial  [24]  anti-inflammatory,  anti-parasitic,  antioxidant,  antitumor  [25]  etc.  Actinobacteria  are  one  of  the  most  efficient  groups  of  biologically  active  secondary  metabolites  producers  and  continue  to  represent  an  exciting  source  for  the  identification  of  novel  natural  products  [26].  Most  of  the  actinobacterial-derived  bioactive  metabolites  have  been  reported  from  terrestrial  sources.  However,  frequent  rediscovery  of  same  compounds  from  terrestrial  origin  have  made  them  less  interesting  and  useful  for  screening  program  in  recent  years.  Marine  actinobacteria  are  known  for  their  intrinsic  chemical  repertoire  [27].  They  were  first  reported  several  decades  ago,  but  it  is  more  recently  they  are  gaining  importance  as  a  source  of  novel  compounds  with  unusual  structures  and  discrete  biological  activities  [28].  They  are  widely  distributed  in  sponges,  seaweeds,  molluscs,  mangroves,  sediments  and  seawater.  The  genus  Streptomyces  contributes  two-thirds  of  all  known  antibiotics and bioactive metabolites up to date [29]. However, the probability of discovery of  novel compounds with new chemical structure from Streptomyces has significantly declined,  mainly  due  to  genetic  exchange  between  species  during  the  course  of  evolution  [30].  environmental locations such as marine source has been given primary importance in recent  times. The rare actinobacteria have been categorised as strains other than commonly known  Streptomyces  or  strains  with  less  frequency  of  isolation  under  conventional  cultivation  techniques [31]. The important rare actinobacteria genera include Frankia, Micromonospora,  Micrococcus, Nocardia, Arthrobacter, Nocardiopsis and several others.

[32]. Andaman and Nicobar Islands marine ecosystem are mostly unexplored and very little  is  known  about  the  rare  actinobacteria  and  their  effective  biomolecules  [33].    Only  limited  research  on  diversity  of  rare  actinobacteria  and  their  metabolites  has  been  reported.  The  authors  have  previously  suggested  the  bioactivity  of  4-methoxyacetanilide,  an  acetamide  derivative  from  marine  actinobacteria  Streptomyces  sp.  SCA29  isolated  from  Havelock  Island, Andaman and Nicobar  Islands, India [34]. Hence, there is an immense possibility to  identify and characterize new marine rare actinobacteria for novel bioactive compounds from  Andaman and Nicobar Islands. Taking this into account, the present study was conducted to  inspect  the  bioactive  potential  of  metabolites  produced  by  rare  actinobacteria  isolated  from  Many reports have encouraged that marine sediment is a rich source of actinobacteria  isolation  and  culturing  of  rare  actinobacteria  from  diverse  marine sediment of Havelock Island, Andaman and Nicobar Islands, India. A total number of  twenty  three  isolates  were  obtained  from  the  marine  sediment  samples.  Of  them,  seven  isolates belonged to the  genus Nocardia (n=3),  Nocardiopsis (n=2) and Nocardioides (n=2)  were identified by molecular characterization of 16S rRNA gene (results not included here).  The solvent extracted metabolites from seven isolates were evaluated for the bioactivity. The  strain  SCA21  was  found  to  be  most  significant  among  all  and  therefore  considered  for  the  study.  The  strain  belonged  to  genus  Nocardiopsis,  was  later  confirmed  by  morphological  identification  and  molecular  characterization  of  16S  rRNA  gene  sequence.  The  resulted

sequences  were  submitted  to  NCBI  under  accession  number  MH105056.  Current  findings  indicate  that  crude  extract  of  SCA21  as  promising  source  of  antibacterial,  antioxidant  and  enzyme inhibition activity. The remarkable potential of crude extract led to the purification,  identification  and  characterization  of  two  compounds  namely,  4-bromophenol  and  Bis(2- ethylhexyl)  phthalate.  Combined  analysis  of  various  chromatographic  and  spectral  studies  was used to validate the structure of purified compounds. In case of accessing the effects of  bioactive compounds on α-glucosidase and α-amylase inhibition, it was found that inhibitory  activity  on  enzyme  was  dose-dependent.  However,  the  inhibitory  effect  of  Compound  2  against α-amylase was observed less significant. The antibacterial efficacy of the compounds  showed potent activity against test pathogens with MIC value ranging from 7.81-125 µg/mL  and  7.81-250  µg/mL  for  compound  1  and  2  respectively.  The  antioxidant  potential  of  the  compounds  was  determined  by  DPPH  and  ABTS  scavenging  assays.  Compound  1  and  2  showed remarkable free radical scavenging potential with IC50 value 187.31 and 96.57µg/mL  against  DPPH  radicals  and  IC50  value  102.22  and  151.60µg/mL  against  ABTS  radicals  respectively. Bis(2,3- dibromo-4,5-dihydroxybenzyl)  ether,  a  marine  bromophenol  derived  from  marine  alga  showed promising inhibitory activity against α-glucosidase [40]. Streptomyces cheonanensis

VUK-A  isolated  from  mangrove  sediment  produced  Diethyl  phthalate  (DEP),  which  exhibited  antibacterial  activity  against  Streptomyces  epidermidis  with  a  MIC  value  of  32  µg/mL. Abd-Elnaby  et  al.  [44]  reported  dioctyl  phthalate  (DIOP) from Streptomyces parvus isolated from marine sediment, which had inhibitory effect  on  cancer  cell  lines.  Al-Bari  et  al.  [45]  reported  the  isolation  of  di  (2-ethylhexyl)  phthalate  from  Streptomyces  bangladeshensis  with  antibacterial  activity.  A  novel  Streptomcyes  strain  TN256,  was  isolated  from  Saharan  soil  produced  di  (2-ethylhexyl)  phthalate  active  against  methicillin-resistant  Staphylococcus  aureus  [46]. Current  study  reported  the  first  time  isolation,  characterization  and  biological  activities  of  compound  1  and  2  from  genus  Nocardiopsis.  The  compound  1  and  2  exhibited  dose-dependent  inhibitory  response  against  α-glucosidase  and  α-amylase  enzymes,  scavenging  effect  against  DPPH  and  ABTS  free  radicals  and  chelation  of  Fe2+.  They  also  showed  potent  antibacterial  activity  against  Marine environment serves as a reservoir of natural bioactive metabolites of wide spectrum  of  chemical  classes.  It  harbours  plethora  of  microorganisms,  screening  and  isolation  of  natural  therapeutic  metabolites  from  unexplored  resources  such  as  rare  actinobacteria  is  a  need  of  the  hour  to  refrain  from  frequent  isolation  of  same  compounds  from  terrestrial  counterparts.  Thus,  this  study  significantly  highlighted  the  isolation,  characterization  and  bioactive potential of metabolites from rare actinobacteria Nocardiopsis sp. SCA21 isolated  from marine sediments. 4-bromophenol and bis-(2-ethylhexyl) phthalate were isolated for the  first time from genus Nocardiopsis which could be further clinically tested and utilized. The  reported  compounds  were  found  to  be  displaying  significant  antioxidant,  enzyme  inhibition  activities  along  with  being  broadly  antibacterial.
